"{\"uid\": \"express.co.uk-celebrity-news-1933644-bbc-gabby-logan-paris-olympics-theory\", \"text\": \"  BBC presenterGabby Loganhas cast doubt over the winner's bell at theParis 2024 Olympics, a revered tradition in athletics events.  The bell is typically rung by winners of events, however, the 51-year-old spotted a potential issue with the timing of the bell during the celebrations. The incident occurred when Sweden's pole-vaulting champion Armand Duplantis triumphantly rang the bell after securing his gold medal.  Sharing her skepticism, Gabby said: \\\"Now, I have noticed this, that the bell starts to ring before the timer actually calls the bell. I am hoping, I am not seeing.. It's like Santa Claus. Is that what I am seeing? Is this a bit of theatre going on down there? \\\", she openly pondered.  BBCpundit and tAmerican sprinter Michael Johnson, jested that perhaps his co-star was just eager for a chance to ring the bell herself. To which Gabby humorously responded: \\\"We will be investigating that, and maybe send you down, Michael.\\\"  READ MORE:Team GB disqualified from Olympics sailing event but still have chance of gold    She added firmly: \\\"In the name of good journalism I want to make sure that that bell is real.\\\"  The tradition dictates that each gold medalist at the Stade de France is afforded the privilege of ringing the bell, which, following the Games, will find a new home at the iconic Notre Dame cathedral    It comes afterGabby bravely opened up about her personal health struggles. The Welsh star revealed she was having memory troubles, which led to her hesitating on-air and proved particularly challenging while covering major events like theOlympicsfor theBBC.  The \\\"brain fog\\\" Gabby experienced is a well-documented symptom of perimenopausea stage, often described by women as feeling like their heads are full of \\\"cotton wool\\\".  Do not miss:Olympian admitted frustration after losing points for accidental nipple flash  Do not miss:Olympian booted out of village after 'cocaine arrest' as he issues apology  Do not miss:Femke Bol's 'Mickey Mouse' voice is not actually real despite viral interviews    However, the former rhythmic gymnast found solace in identifying the cause of her forgetfulness. To help combat this, she adopted the method of keeping a piece of paper with her on-set to quickly note down names.  In a candid interview with The Telegraph, Gabby shared: \\\"I did not realise when I first started to experience the symptoms, [and] it was so alien to me to not be able to recall that I was starting to think, 'Oh God, I just can not remember stuff any more'.  We use your sign-up to provide content in ways you have consented to and to improve our understanding of you. This may include adverts from us and 3rd parties based on our understanding. You can unsubscribe at any time. Read ourPrivacy Policy  \\\"I was always so good at recall. I got through a law degree basically just by going, 'Ah, page 32, Smith versus Cook'. I was always good with names, finding the right word at the right time, and I'd find myself umming a bit or using 'very, very, very'.  SEARCH  CONNECT WITH US  TODAY'S PAPER  See today's front and back pages, download the newspaper, order back issues and use the historic Daily Express newspaper archive.  EXPRESS.CO.UK  Daily Express uses notifications to keep you updated\"}"